🙂 I will keep an open mind, I really want to get to a good solution.

> What's the cost in ns of a single call to RemoteSegment or InlineSegment?

I suppose you are worried because it is a virtual function call which inherently comes with some overhead?

I think I can deduce that it is negligible: The fastest observer on US1 is ~5 minutes out of ~8 hours. It is [not a trivial implementation](https://github.com/storj/storj/blob/68fe26ebe56f874281caf89eefbbb0facc31e431/satellite/metrics/counter.go#L52). It processes 350M segments. 5m / 350M = 850ns per segment.

If we want to measure more accurately we can attach NullObserver.

I do see that the loop does 2(!) calls to get the system time per Segment. 1 of these is prolly counted in the 850ns and the other in the 30% overhead (most of the 30% will be database ofc). Maybe it would be a bigger win to optimize this?

I did some benchmarking of the solutions below with 25000 segments. I tried to trick it so it doesn't devirtualize.

```go
type SingleObserver interface {
	Process(*Segment)
}

type NullSingleObserver struct {
}

func (n NullSingleObserver) Process(s *Segment) {
}

func observeSingle(observer SingleObserver, segments []Segment) time.Duration {
    start := time.Now()
    for _, s := range segments {
        observer.Process(&s)
    }
    return time.Since(start)
}
```

2.5 ns/segment

```go
func observeSingleWithTime(observer SingleObserver, segments []Segment) (total time.Duration, inner time.Duration) {
	start := time.Now()

	var duration time.Duration = 0
	for _, s := range segments {
		start := time.Now()
		observer.Process(&s)
		duration = duration + time.Since(start)
	}

	return time.Since(start), duration
}
```

1100 ns/segment inner loop (so this is slower than the counter observer in prod)
3300 ns/segment outer loop 

```
type MultiObserver interface {
	Process([]Segment)
}

type NullMultiObserver struct {
	count int
}

func (n NullMultiObserver) Process(segments []Segment) {
	for _, s := range segments {
		// call a non-virtual function so the comparison is kinda fair
		n.Add(&s)
	}
}

func (n NullMultiObserver) Add(segment *Segment) {
	// do an op so the optimizer doesn't elide this function
	n.count += segment.a
}
```

0.24 ns/segment

Conclusion about []Segment vs *Segment: the difference is 2.25 ns/segment. For 350M segments this is 100ms per observer. Optimization isn't worth it.

Conclusion about timers: in my benchmark this takes over 3 ms/segment. For 350M segments this is 18 minutes per observer. We should optimize this.

> The point here is that it will allow to make observers concurrent without needing to implement Spawn and Combine.

I don't understand this. If I have an observer like this:

```
class Observer {
    count: int

    Observe(segments []Segment) error {
        for _, s := segments {
            count++;
        }
    }
}
```

How do I make it threadsafe? Can you please provide a pseudo-code interface with implementation of a counter?

